                <note rend="inline" type="source">662.116 Lard/20: Telegram (part air)</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-05-28T20:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 28, 1934—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>68. Please discuss with the Foreign Office, and supplement with an <hi
                        rend="italic">Aide-Mémoire</hi>, the factual material embodied in your
                    telegrams Nos. 91 and 94 of May 18 and 22.</p>
                <p>You should point out that this Government considers that the figures in question
                    represent unequal treatment of American lard imports and as such conflict with
                    Article 7 of our Treaty of December 8, 1923. In calling attention to this
                    situation you should express the hope that early measures will be taken to
                    assure American lard exporters no less favorable treatment than that accorded
                    others.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
